The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Sports | Briefs
                                                                                                                       7                                                                                                      
	CA nod to new format  
	Calcutta: Cricket Australia Friday approved a controversial 45-over, split innings one-day format for trial in this seasons national one-day cup. The new format envisages 45 overs per team with split innings of 20 and 25 overs, a maximum of 12 overs by any one bowler and 10 wickets per team and 12 players per team (teams can bat any 11 of the 12 and field any 11 of the 12), among other changes.      
	Jaipur: A court in Jodhpur has served a notice on Rajasthan Cricket Association secretary Sanjay Dixit, asking him to explain how he could hold the post despite being an IAS officer.      
	CWG team  
	New Delhi: Leander Paes and Mahesh Bhupathi were Friday named in the Indian mens squad for the Commonwealth Games along with Somdev Dev Varman and Rohan Bopanna.       
	New Delhi: The All India Tennis Association announced that it would follow the sports ministrys directives on the controversial tenure regulations after it arrived at the decision at its executive committee meeting here.      
	Negi loses  
	Warsaw: GM Parimarjan Negi suffered a crushing defeat against top seed Dmitry Andreikin but Padmini Rout kept herself in contention after Round IX in the world junior chess championship on Friday.  
	India win  
	Lisbon: Mohammed Rafis first-half strike saved India the blushes as they eked out a narrow 1-0 win over Portuguese club Real Massama in a practice match here.      
	Calcutta: Hariyana Vidya Mandir entered the semis of the All Bengal Mega Finals of the Dabur RedTTIS Shootout 10 beating South Eastern Railway Boys High School (Kharagpur) 3-0, at the Harish Park ground, on Friday. The other teams to make it to the last four are Kenduadihi Madhyamik Institution (Bankura), St Michaels School (Siliguri) and Durgapur Project Boys School.                                                                                                                                                      
